A republican strategy to counter the re-election of Obama
The republican leaders justified their policy by the need for fighting against the electoral fraud.
However, the Center Brennan regards the latter as a myth, affirming that the electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by the lightning.
Moreover, the republican lawyers listed only 300 cases of fraud electoral in the United States in ten years.
A thing is certain: these new provisions will influence rate of participation negatively.
In this direction, these measurements will undermine the American democratic system partly.
Contrary to Canada, the American States are responsible for the organization of the federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of US governments promulgated starting from 2009 new laws making more difficult the process of registration or vote.
This phenomenon gained in importance after the elections of November 2010 which transfer to be added 675 new republican representatives in 26 States.
Consequently, 180 government bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 States were introduced during the only year of 2011.
The new electoral laws require that the voters present an identity card with photograph and a proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce also the periods of advance voting, invalidate the right to be registered like voter the day of the poll and withdraw with the citizens having a legal file their right to vote.
Before the elections of 2006, no American State required voters to present an identity card with photograph.
Indiana was the first State to establish such a requirement.
The Supreme court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the law of Indiana.
The republican authorities hastened to extend this practice in other States.
During two last years, they sponsored government bills in 34 States to force the voters to present an identity card with photograph.
It is important to note that, contrary to Quebec, the American citizens do not have universal identity card like the chart of the health insurance.
In fact, 11% of the American citizens, are 21 million people in age to vote, do not have identity cards with photograph emitted by a governmental agency of their State.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 does not have such identification papers.
However, it costs some often more than one hundred dollars to obtain the necessary identity card.
The new restrictions assign in a disproportionate way the young people, the minorities, and the people with low-income.
Indeed, 25% of the Afro-Americans, 15% of the people gaining less than 35,000 dollars; 18% of the citizens of more than 65 years and 20% of the voters from 18 to 29 years do not have the necessary identity card with photograph.
Much more.
The students, of the voters considered as voter more for the democratic candidates, are not authorized in several States to use their identity card with photograph emitted by their institution.
On the other hand, these same States authorize the members of the clubs of peaches or hunting which vote more on the republican side to use to vote the cards emitted by these clubs.
Before 2004, no State required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen States adopted laws requiring of the voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measurements clearly aim at limiting the Hispanic vote.
However, it Appert whom two Hispanic voters out of three support the democratic party.
In addition, the republican legislators sponsored in 2011 laws abolishing the registration of the voters the day of the poll in eight States.
Moreover, they limited the right of people and groups to provide an assistance to the voters wishing to be registered.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, at the time of the general election of 2004, the registration campaigns of the voters contributed to record approximately 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 made fall of 17% the rate of registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
Moreover, the republican legislators adopted laws in five other States aiming at reducing the period of advance voting.
For example, at the time of the general election of 2008 in Florida, 33% of the voters who have advance voting were Afro-Americans, whereas the latter accounted for only 13% of the voters of the State.
The same applied with the Hispanic ones.
Those accounted for only 11% from the voters, but 24% citizens who voted by anticipation.
On the other hand, the white which formed 76% of the voters accounted for only 46% of the voters voter by anticipation.
Of course the democratic legislators and their supporters opposed the adoption of laws vigorously restricting the registration of the voters.
Several government bills were blocked by the vetoes of the democratic governors.
The prosecuting attorney of the United States intervened to suspend the most discussed laws.
They could limit the damage partly.
For example, only 16 out of 34 States adopted laws requiring the presentation of an identity card with photograph.
Nevertheless, the new rules installation unquestionably will make more difficult the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
The democratic critics denounce the character in favour of the laws which were voted and they see an obvious objective there to influence the results in 2012 in key States.
A report of the Center Brennan of 2011 shows that the States which adopted these laws account for 171 of the 270 votes necessary to the electoral college to gain the presidency.
It is too early to affirm with certainty that these legislative modifications on the level of the electoral system will have significant impacts on the result of the presidential elections of 2012.
But a thing is certain: these new provisions will influence rate of participation negatively.
In this direction, these measurements will undermine the American democratic system partly.

