# genre=news sysid=rbmt-1 origlang=fr docid=lemondefr/2012/12/01/275696
With Bitcoin, to pay and sell without the banks
All the opposite of the current monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and expenses of treatment enters the recipients.
Moreover, like often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made banking monopolies, led to the financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is at the same time a virtual currency (but convertible in dollars, euros…) and a protocol of exchange made safe in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the file-swapping of par par.
Approximately 200,000 transactions were already recorded thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
A small thousand of Web sites accept the bitcoins like gifts or means of payment.
The course of the bitcoin, after having reached a top of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell with 2 dollars, five months later, before returning today around ten dollars (the courses are listed on the bitcoincharts.com site).
Nothing very impressive, compared to world exchanges in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central bank (ECB) was interested there in a report on the virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin like “the currency virtual having the most success”, “competing with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin is distinguished from other types of virtual currency like the “appropriations”, used to progress in a video game which one gains while playing or which one can buy (and sometimes to exchange in return).
The Facebook social network also developed this kind of system.
But, each time, a central authority controls and treats the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all the nodes of the network are at the same time agents of the book of accounts, inspectors, transmitters of currency, and purchasers and salesmen.
How does this network function?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the manner of e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of related information with this transaction is signed electronically by a system of coding to double key.
The network can thus check the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is as possible to make sure as the exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public book of accounts, diffused in all the network.
The stage-key consists in writing this new transaction in this book.
It passes by the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to the computers, and whose winner, left provisional central banker, will have the privilege to add this additional line.
It is about a phase of chopping of file, i.e. of transformation of a large file into a shorter and single digital print.
The computers “take” the new transaction and add to him a number before “chopping” the unit.
The goal being to find the number which gives a particular print (many of zeros at the beginning).
Once this found number, the other nodes check easily that it is the good.
The transaction is then indestructiblement related to the chain of the whole of the other transactions; any modification would change the print.
If, to defraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because both have different prints.
The computer having solved the challenge gains 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they are divisible until the hundred millionth, which leaves margin…
The difficulty of the challenge is also raised with each increase of the computing power.
The life of the network already had tops and bottoms.
Providing Web sites of the services for Bitcoin were attacked and the bitcoins in stolen deposits.
“The fault used does not relate to the protocol itself”, Pierre Noizat ensures, who has just launched Paymium, a company of payment in true currency using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB mentions also possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash also has this defect.
Serious actors as Wikipedia refuse the gifts of this nature.
Others, like the platform of blogs WordPress, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the book of accounts and showed that nearly 80% of the bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, “giant balances” were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged”, is delighted Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of a teaching book on this currency, believes much in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, are equivalent to a credit card (in true currency) or to a payment by mobile without contact, but it uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions, which cost thus less.
The carrier manages moreover its identity and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement in the merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to communicate an address which a telephone can “photograph and recognize”, Pierre Noizat specifies, who ensures to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of reconsideration of the hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will be necessary time so that Bitcoin is essential, but 2013 could be revolving”, he predicts.
Besides The ECB, in his report, envisages to revalue the various risks, now considered as raised, in the event of success of this currency.

