# genre=news sysid=rbmt-1 origlang=cs docid=idnes.cz/2012/12/01/494025
Poland and cosmos.
Last week, during the ministerial meeting of the countries of the European space agency, Poland was allowed as twentieth member of this agency, it is the second Member State of the old Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became member except for whole on November 12th, 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with the ESA in 1994 and during years which followed took part in a number of projects of the agency.
The road of Poland towards space however began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, of the impassioned Poles worked on space flights; they always did not meet comprehension.
I would like to evoke for example the conference of A. Šternfeld at the astronomical observatory of Warsaw, on December 6th, 1933, during which it presented ideas drawn from its work of avant-garde entitled “Introduction to astronautics”.
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the cold listeners and of the years later Šternfeld remembered that only Doctor Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld obtained in France the price Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his work “Introduction to astronautics”.
The aforementioned Doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) became thereafter a large propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
It published hundreds of articles in the Polish newspapers and wrote many dedicated works with this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of the astronautics of world famous, its contribution was in particular rewarded by the fact that its name was given to the one of the craters of the hidden side of the Moon.
By 1925 was built in Poland a line inspection car intended to be been driven by a rocket motor.
One knows neither the author unfortunately nor the details of this project.
It is not clearly either if the rocket were to be used for propelling or braking the line inspection car.
The only information known on this line inspection car is those of the press of the time.
Starting from 1933, the Polish artillery started to be devoted to the rockets.
The researches were undertaken by the institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It arises from the preserved documents that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, research stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric rocket of hunting, drawn by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the work “Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna I rakietobomba lotnicza” of an author called Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects had as a finality a military use of the engines of rockets.
Right before the war, all the projects of use of the technique of the rockets were carried out by the provisional advisory scientific committee (“Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy”), which coordinated all work.
This committee had been created in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war put an end to its activities.
After the war, the other work devoted to aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the company Polish astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is question of a company in the number of November 1954 of the newspaper Problem, in which four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics are.
In one of these articles, written by professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a company devoted to astronautics
At that time, projects of artificial satellites had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had future.
With the beginning of the year 1956, the company Polish astronautics (PTA) made efforts to enter international the astronautics federation (created in 1951) and as of the autumn, the PTA became a regular member about it.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of international the astronautics federation.
It preserved its function until its death in 1959.
Starting from 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the crowned development of success of the weather rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific researches.
The first model, RM-1, were finished in 1957 and the first launching took place on October 10th, 1958.
This rocket of a range of 1800 meters had a 80 cm length and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Thereafter was built an improved version, RM-1A and, during the summer 1959, of the tests of flight of the rocket on two floors RM-2 were started in the desert of Bledov.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meter and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - rocket RM-34 should have had a range going up to 14.5 km and have been used to observe the wind in altitude.
But in 1963, all work of development was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first rockets of the type RM.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had an overall length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were characterized by dimensions from reserved space to the scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liter, while in Meteor-1B this volume was of 0.34 liter and in Meteor-1C of 0.62 liter.
The maximum range of all these types of machine was of 37 km.
During the time 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first tests of flight began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
Thereafter the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is still advisable to mention the entry of Poland with the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national committee COSPAR two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland also took part in space exploration on the artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second cosmonaut not-Soviet of this program.

