The Argo film: when all goes to most badly, to call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a bunch of demonstrators made up of islamist students took attack the American embassy of Teheran and retained hostages 52 diplomats.
They were to be released in return for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled in the United States, which had supported its mode for several decades.
The situation did not offer to the American administration of positive exit, it could not, indeed, give up the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic mode, it was not able to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a heavy blow for the prestige of the United States, blow still worsened later by the fiasco of the attempt at release of the hostages by the force.
The sequestered diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following the negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate caused in the United States a wave of solidarity and a feeling anti-Iranian.
The Iranian rout strongly contributed to the defeat of Jimmy Carter vis-a-vis Ronald Reagan with the presidential elections of 1980.
The Argo film, of the actor and director Ben Affleck, described an episode of this history which offered a small victory to America.
Just before it is occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated adventures, they were found in the residence of the ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to make them leave Iran thanks to a fantastic cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a team of turning come to make locations for the turning of a film with large show of science fiction.
Combination of the kinds
The plan of the expert in exfiltration Tony Mendez required the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, of store specialized mentioned this project of film, of the press conferences were organized and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained a long time secret, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
The film of Affleck is an unusual combination several kinds.
It is on the one hand about a conceived political thriller in a realistic way but also one “to wrap movie”, the account at a stretch successful, of a treachery - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean' S eleven, twelve and thirteen.
Environments follow one another: sequences of documentary Teheran of style (in the subtitled sequences iconic photographs of the time of the events and the manner are presented whose, thanks to these photographs, these same situations were retranscribed in the film, it does not have there great differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes of the general headquarter of the CIA and other institutions with dressed up men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the telephone…
Ben Affleck succeeded in starting again his career in a remarkable way.
Of ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and its game of actor ceased causing ironic remarks.
Argo is its third feature film after the dark police officer “Gone Gone Baby” (2007) and the thriller “The town” (2010).
It is also the first film of Affleck which is not held in its town of origin, Boston.
The direction of the atmosphere of a place constitutes one of the characteristics which placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also shows this direction of the atmosphere in Argo where the role of Teheran “is held” by Canada.
The best scenes of the film are held in streets, during the reconstruction of actual facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clearness which also suggests confusion and the unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and its collaborators obtain a similar effect in the fictitious scenes (team of turning in the bazaar of Teheran distorts it).
Too many actions to too many places
The director had to be satisfied with a subject not offering in fact that few palpitating scenes, with the cinematographic direction of the term.
It is left there extremely well, it adds sometimes certain elements with reality and there, the result is not always also elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis to the airport of Teheran is drawn aside by a telephone call in America and the continuation on the runway are drawn enough by the hair).
The weakness of Argo lies in its dissipated character, which had with the need for showing too many events to too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are completely charming in their role of Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a larger place and it is not, far from there, only in this case.
The film of Affleck misses a little dramatic tension, it is let see with a moderated interest, by appreciating the realization and the pre-1940s style of the Seventies.
It involves the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a recall of a history still, in a certain way, unfinished to date, and like illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of the secret services like omnipotent and omniscient, he gets the bargain.

