Szabo: “the Germans must play a greater part.”
Germany chose the abstention at the time of the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert of the relations between the United States and the EU, this decision put Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the request of Palestinian to obtain the statute of observant State at the United Nations.
But it then chose the abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must show prudence, because it maintains the particular relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support either the American position.
Germany wanted to affirm its independence, without however showing itself too critical towards Israel.
At the time of the insurrection in Libya of March 2011, Germany had also chosen the abstention at the time of the vote on the installation from a zone of air exclusion.
Finally, NATO imposed this measurement.
Does Germany have difficulty of adopting a clear position in connection with the great international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is re-examining its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak definite by the Americans and to found a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans thus encounter several faces.
It is waited them until they play a more independent part, but they are not accustomed there.
I believe that they still grope to find this role, but are on the way of a foreign politics “more normal”.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What then means concretely the term of foreign politics “normal” for the Germans?
It shows the will to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to the national files.
I believe that the German foreign politics is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and his relationships to certain areas, like Russia, China or the Middle East.
The German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other great powers: this is why Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position of Germany with respect to the conflict in the Middle East and the abstention at the time of the vote of the United Nations?
Germany has initially important outlets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
This is why Berlin must take care not to run up against the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
It is without any doubt a crucial factor.
However, I would not grant too much importance to it, because it is not about exclusively unilateral relation.
But it is there in any case a crucial factor in the German strategic reflections.
Does Germany harm its relations with the United States by choosing the abstention at the time of important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and the Americans understand the German position perfectly.
This is why I think that the fracture is not so serious that it was it in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even as Germany only will be respected of it.
Indeed, Germany thus showed that it must be taken with serious as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the opinions concerning the Palestinian initiative are varied.
On the other hand, the United States announced their veto of a clear voice.
Do the opinions differ between the United States and the majority from the European countries?
There always were differences because of the scene American domestic policy.
I believe that the Administration Obama secretly shown a great comprehension towards the European position.
But considering the political configuration of the country, the government cannot of course defend its position publicly.
I believe that the true differences in opinions are not so large that they always appear it.
If you observe the relations between Obama and Israeli the Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing of enthusiasm with regard to the policy of Netanyahou.
Does Germany have difficulty of reconciling its close relationships with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the large European partners, on the other hand?
I think that does not facilitate the things for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today, it is not the case.
They cannot thus be registered within a vaster political line and must affirm their singular position.
It is what they currently do in the question of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will assume a role of engine in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, in particular because of relations with Israel.
This question was always delicate.
But in my opinion, the Germans are quite conscious owing to the fact that they must play a part which marks their independence more.
Does Germany see itself playing a part of serious actor on the international scene, Germany wants it only to assume one key function?
Or does she always have difficulties in assuming leading roles?
Germany is still not accustomed there, that is always uncomfortable for him and, in obvious reasons, the country always has difficulty of playing a more important part.
If one looks at, for example, the crisis of the euro, one notices that with each time Germany decides to weigh more, of many feelings antiallemands are made hear.
That does not facilitate the things for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: one does not want to be encircled hostile countries.
This point seen, Germany is in a position much more delicate than the United States.
It must compose with neighbors and opinions very varied, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on the European policy do nothing but decrease, but currently, the EU does not fill this vacuum, then which does it does remain?
The Germans will have simply to play a more important part.
And even if they do not like that, even if that their is unpleasant and if they only are appreciated of it, it is life!
Stephen Szabo is the assistant editor of Transatlantic Academy of Washington, an institute in which academics and experts in policy of Europe and North America analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community together.
Szabo is also member of German Marshall Fund, where it specialized in German policy, American foreign politics and transatlantic relations.

