Messenger: NASA discovers the presence of ice on Mercury
The Messenger probe brought back evidence of the existence of ice on the planet Mercury.
The layer of ice could reach 20 meters thickness.
American space agency NASA proved the existence of ice on the planet Mercury.
Although this planet is closest to the Sun, it contains frozen water, as three studies published explain it this Thursday in the specialized magazine “Science”.
The Messenger probe brought back evidence of the existence of a cover of ice in the area of planet permanently plunged in the shade.
This cover would have a thickness of at least 30 centimetres being able to go up to 20 meters.
Water probably comes from comets or perhaps from asteroids which would have run up against Mercury.
However, nobody establishes link between the water discovery and the assumption of a presence of life on planet, explains in chief scientist of the probe Messenger, Sean Solomon.
The temperature on Mercury can reach 426 degrees Celsius.
