In a world constantly connected, it can be good to be bored.
I spent five hours in an airport for the period of Thanksgiving, because our plane had mechanical problems and we had to expect the arrival of another plane.
Consequently, I had sufficient time to think of the topic of the trouble.
I will not lie you.
To spend one half-day in an airport to expect a flight is rather tedious, even when you have books, magazines and iPhones to distract you (without forgetting the shops of duty-free).
But more and more, certain academics and experts specialized in the development of the child speak in praise of the trouble.
It is perfectly normal for us - and our children - to be bored from time to time, they say.
That forces the brain to take interesting ways, to even nourish the creativity.
And as we are, for the majority, constantly in front of several types of screens, we do not know any more the benefits of the trouble.
Then should we accommodate the trouble with open arms?
Yes.
And not.
But I will return there.
First of all, following the example of much of people, I thought that the trouble was a rather recent phenomenon, in particular since we have more free time.
But it is not the case, declares Peter Toohey, professor of history gréco-Roman at the University of Calgary, with Canada, and author of “Boredom: In Lively History” (Yale University Press, 2011).
“The trouble goes back to very far”, he says.
On the walls of Pompéi are reproduced of the Latin graffiti which evoke the trouble, they go back to the first century.
Then, there is the definition which we give to the trouble.
The problem is that it was defined, and discussed, in various ways, declared John D. Eastwood, qualified schoolteacher of psychology in York University in Ontario, Canada.
After having traversed many publications and subjected the idea to a newsgroup of approximately 100 people, Professeur Eastwood and his colleagues defined the trouble as being an experiment which consists in “wanting to do something, but without managing to launch out in a satisfactory activity.”
What differentiates the trouble from apathy, he says, it is that the person is not undertaking a task although she would wish it.
With apathy, he says, it does not want there to do something.
What is in the middle of the trouble, he declared, it is “the interruption of the process of attention, associated with a gloomy mood and the feeling which time passes slowly.”
The trouble can strongly resemble a depression.
But Professeur Eastwood declared that if both can be dependent, the people who are bored tend to think that the problem comes from the environment or the world, while the depressed people think that the problem comes from them.
Sometimes, it sometimes happens to us to think that we are bored whereas it acts by way of a problem of concentration.
Within the framework of their study, “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention”, which was published in the newspaper “Prospects one Psychological Science” in September, Professeur Eastwood and his colleagues highlighted an older experiment in which the participants listened on cassette, the voice of a person reading an article of magazine.
Certain groups heard, coming from the room at side, the too high sound of an emission of TV which did not have any report, others just heard the emission of TV, and the third group did not hear at all bandage it.
Those which heard the TV on a low noise level said that they had been bored more than the two other groups - they had evil to concentrate, but did not know why, and allotted this problem of concentration to the trouble.
When you try to concentrate you on a difficult or fascinating task, an interruption of the attention can lead to the trouble, declared Mark J. Fenske, a qualified schoolteacher of neuroscience in University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you carry out a tedious task, “like looking at objects on an assembly line, the music can help you not to annoy you.”
In fact, he says, now, we know that when one twists oneself or that one scribbles, these gestures, often considered as signs of trouble, are in fact a good means of remaining physically more alert.
“Studies showed that the children who are authorized to wriggle learn more and retain more information than those which are forced to remain without moving”, Professeur Fenske declared.
We are bored a whole day or the other - the delay of my flight of plane, a speaker with a monotonous voice, a particularly tedious film.
But certain people are more likely to be bored than others.
To measure that, of the researchers developed a “Scale of predisposition to the trouble” in the Eighties.
The scale includes assertions like, “Among the tasks which I carry out, much of them are repetitive and monotonous”, and “I have centers of interest so much that I do not have time to do everything.”
By using such a scale, the researchers discovered that the boys tend to be bored more often than the girls, declared Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology in University of West Florida, and need in particular many and varied stimulations.
But in general, the teenagers are quickly blasé.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor under development individual and Community in University of Illinois, undertook an experiment during which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times per day via one to beep.
It raised that 32 percent of the teenagers stated to be bored at the school and during their duties at the house, while 23 percent stated to be bored when they were not at the school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of the parents stated to be bored.
Professor Larson declared that it did not know if the percentages of trouble of today, is 21 years later, would be raised or lower.
But he added that he knew that “adolescence is one period when the trouble reaches its more high level”, in particular because the children and the teenagers do not have much control on what they want to do.
If I rest my question: is the trouble good for you?
Sometimes not, because in its extreme form, that can involve the people to take absurd physical chances, to make bets or to misuse certain substances to spend the time, as the studies show it.
On the other hand, of many philosophers and writers evoke a bond between the trouble and the creativity, declared the Professeur Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
“The trouble is the means which the brain found to state to you that you should make another thing”, declared Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology to the N.Y.U.
But the brain always does not know which is the thing most adapted to make.
If you are bored and that you use this energy to play of the guitar and to cook, that will return to you happy.
But if you look at the TV, that will return to you happy in the short run, but not in the long run.
Then if your child is bored and that you give him a iPad, it will not be bored any more, but it will not have learned how to be occupied all alone nor with autorégler, declares professor Fenske.
And “this autorèglement passes from a situation to another”, he declares.
Your child does not only learn how to divert himself, it obtains more control of itself in other fields.
I do not think that we should glorify the trouble.
Just like I do not think either that we should criticize it.
To feel at ease apart from the constant boiling that generate the activities and technology is the objective towards which should tend to us.
Professor Eastwood is of agreement on this point.
“We need to more often annoy us, but the trouble wakes up an acute and frantic desire to be connected to something which has direction”, he declared.
According to him, which people search, it is a means of disconnecting and of appreciating the downtimes.
“In an environment where we constantly are hyperstimulés”, he added, “it is difficult to find ways of launching out in something when the noise stops.”

