The hardest trade of the world: human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their life and their health while carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others which work literally in hell.
It is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 minors who earn a living while carrying the sulphur of the volcano Kawah Ijen, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work each until the underground of the crater, where the sulphuric gas emanating from the entrails of the ground is solidified in contact with the air.
After having collected large sulphur rocks, which weigh on the whole nearly 70 kilos, it installs them in two shopping carts in bamboo which it charges on its shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano which culminates with 2.386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers put more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, with a pace of tortoise, by keeping balance and measuring their steps not to stumble and fall into the chasm.
They know that a false step could cost them the life, as that arrived to a French tourist who fell a deadly fall in the volcano Kawah Ijen several years ago.
The minors of Kawah Ijen gain 5 centimes of euro for each kilo of extracted sulphur.
Once in top, it frayent a way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were animals of circus, and carrying the heavy shopping carts painfully, they go the 3 kilometers to the balance which a mining company installed a little downwards with 1.850 meters of altitude.
It is about Pt Candi Ngrimbi, a company which exploits the volcano since 1960 and, one can say it, its employees, with whom he pays 662 rupees Indonesian (5 centimes of euro) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it with 10.000 rupees (83 centimes of euro) with petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in the daily life and is used to manufacture candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and is even used to bleach sugar.
“As we transport approximately 70 kilos, we gain approximately 46.000 rupees (3.8 euros) with each travel”, explains us Anto, which makes three journeys per day in general.
Each one takes 3 hours to him and it finishes exhausted, but that enables him to gain 138.000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although that appears to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is triple of what it would gain in the fields.
“The income of the minors is very here high, where the harvest of the coffee is paid 15.000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the monthly average wages are of two million rupees (167 euros)”, the carrier declares which worked formerly as mason on the tourist island of Bali.
Over there, its wages were of 75.000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not also difficult, but Anto returned close to its family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason which, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulphur: “I married an young girl of Bali, where they are hindouists, and I brought back it to Java so that it converts with Islam”.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and its eyes are irritated by poison gazs.
At 27 years, it passed three of its life to defy the danger on Kawah ljen, but sulphur already started to make him pay the invoice although it covers the face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and its eyes are irritated by poison gazs rejected by the volcano.
It is the price which it must pay to continue its dreamed.
“I will work two more years, because I want to open a shop or to study Spanish or French” promises he in English more than acceptable.
Abused by the life, this nice and intelligent young person could be tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but, instead of that, it does the work of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wood hovel with other carriers, is lifted each day to a height of two hours of the morning because sulphur does not cease spouting out the night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto goes down in the crater in lighting with a small lamp fixed at its helmet, which it bought itself with its own money.
Some 400 carriers load the shopping carts with sulphur on their shoulders since the bottom of the crater.
In spite of its comfortable benefit, the mining company did not mechanize the extraction of sulphur to save the costs and does not provide any equipment to the carriers which work on their account and are paid with the weight.
Moreover, they do not touch either under 30.000 rupees (2.50 euros) of increase per camera, besides the entry of 15.000 rupees (1.20 euros), that the guards of this natural park invoice with the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and his human mules.
“This work is made for the animals, not for the human ones”, protests Madrusin, a corpulent carrier 42 years which has worked in Kawah Ijen for thirty years, since it left the college.
Able to carry up to 110 kilos, it ensures that it will not stop working “as long as it will be able it”, because it needs money to raise his 3 sons, old between 10 and 18 years.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is all my life.
Although sulphur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the minors in the thick columns of smoke which leave the volcano, they are so hardened that nobody complains to suffer from the serious diseases… to which are added obviously their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritides, pains in the knees and the shoulders, deformed by the weight of the shopping carts.
By balancing the shopping cart on its back, Unainik, 53 years old, can only charge 50 kilos.
Each day, its companions and extract 15 tons to him from sulphur of the volcano, that three trucks transport to the warehouse of Tamansari, to 18 kilometers from there by a path of goats invaded by weeds.
“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is all my life”, Unainik affirms by opening the mouth well, revealing several missing teeth.
The elder one of his/her five children, 30 years old, also works like sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but misery from generation to generation perpetuates one of the most difficult trades in the world: that which the human mules of the volcano Kawah ljen do.

# genre=news sysid=rbmt-1 origlang=es docid=bbc/spanish/2012/12/01/18527
Singapore searches babies to save the economy
The Singaporeans throw the responsibility for this absence of children on the career, the stress and the cost of the access to the property.
“The population of Singapore must develop”.
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, let us fill our civic duty and give the life!
It can appear incredible that these words come from a publicity for pastilles to mint, but in spite of that, or perhaps thanks to that, the video was spread like a powder trail on YouTube in Singapore at the beginning of this year.
The words come from a group of rap which uses local references as “will put Punchinello in the drawer” to make fun of the birth rate of Singapore.
BBH, the advertising agency at the origin of the video, hope to draw attention to the problem in a way amusing thanks to this publicity.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, declared that it wished to use the power of the music so that people fill “their national duty”.
It is intended only for the Internet, we thus could return it diverting and amusing.
It is the principal problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of the birthrate, thus we felt that it was a topic that we must approach.
We knew that the government had tried several things like launching perfumes to the phéromones or organizing evenings of speed-dating.
Many of these ideas were creative but they inevitably did not function.
We thus said ourselves the following thing: what could be more creative to solve this problem than to make a song of rap of it?
1.2 children
The government of Singapore does not take it as much with the light one.
He spends 1.300 US dollars a year in policies to encourage his citizens to have more children.
A measurement of the government in favour as of marriages and the fathers grants to 15.000 dollars per child, lengthens the maternity leave and distributes pre-tax profits.
But all that had few effects.
Singapore is city-state rich and of high technology of the South-east of Asia, such a known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
The birth rate of Singapore, in accordance with its national distribution of population, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time that it was above 2, regarded as the it, renewal rate was in 1976.
Why thus the Singaporeans have don't more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the policies of the marriage and the family of the National Division of the Population, affirms that it is due to a “better education” and with “a broader choice of career appropriatenesses”.
“That made it possible to people to have a broader range of options in terms of objectives of life and priorities, beyond the marriage and of the constitution of a family”, she explains.
These changes of the social norms contributed to the increase amongst single people and to delay the marriage and the births, which has as a result a reduction in birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aiming at radically increasing immigration to counter the reduction in the population created a resentment within the local population.
In Singapore, one finds Web sites who abounds a xenophobia hardly disguised against the new immigrants, in particular towards the Chinese who are shown to draw the wages to the bottom and not to be integrated.
The increase in immigration is also perceived as one of the reasons for which the party in place in Singapore knew last year its worst election results since independence.
Since the elections, they tried to correct the problem with the installation of quotas and higher taxes for the foreign workers.
Unhoped-for consequences
Whereas the fall of birth rate has effects known on the economic growth of a country, the tax incomes, the medical costs and the immigration policies, the example of Singapore also has unexpected consequences.
The government tries to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, that started to affect the real sector.
The authorities of the urban development started to control the number of small apartments, known under the name of “box with shoes”, being able to be built in given zones of the city.
These apartments have a surface of 46 square meters and their sale gains much success.
However, the authorities are worried by the fact that they can promote a lifestyle of single person and discourage the promoters wishing to build large family houses.
But Lim Yew Soon, chief executive officer of real estate company EL Developers, affirms that its “boxes with shoes” are sold much more quickly than the larger residences.
They are more popular, in the direction where these residences are built much more quickly than those of bigger size.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to the promoters, with which one put before sticks in the wheels if they wished to propose too many small residences in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-State.
If as well is as these new regulations can be a step towards the increase in national birth rate, while discussing with the Singaporeans who work in the financial district of the center, it would seem that they will not have much effects.
“People are very stressed, the houses are expensive, just like education, therefore people gives it to later”, a junior manager declares.
The other people can have children.
“But for me, it is important to be able to have my money and of my time”, another young person of about twenty years declares us.
The men and the women mention their career, the stress and the cost of the access to the property and education like the reasons preventing them from having children.
Thus, although the government tries to convince its citizens to have children, when it is a question of making babies, they are the Singaporeans themselves which have the last word.

