The top of Unasur finished without the Declaration of Lima being made public
The Life presidential top of the Union of the South American nations (Unasur) finished today in Peru without the Declaration of Lima being made public, although she was announced previously and theoretically adopted by the 7 agents present.
Efe tried on several occasions to reach the document signed at the time of the Ordinary Life Réunion of the Heads of States and government of Unasur, but the Ministry for Foreign Affairs and the presidency announced at the beginning that it would be revealed after the top closure, then affirmed that it would be published from one moment to another on the website of the Peruvian government.
When they were questioned on the text, they announced that its contents had been reported on the president of Peru, Ollante Humala, at the time of short declarations to the press.
The access of the journalists to information concerning the top was constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message “session private, audio restricted” was diffused in the press room.
The little of information which circulated between the journalists was those given by the press agents of some of the governments of Unasur who assisted with go, except for Peruvian spokesperson.
The single document revealed at the time of the day was the list of the presidents present, which caused a certain discomfort at the hundreds of journalists of various national mediums and international which claimed more important information.
Later, the presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the “final declaration” of the top, but it was the speech of president Humala and not of the official document which concluded the top.
Last October, Peru was the host of the 3rd America top of the Arab South-Countries (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although that was required with authority by the press, he had not diffused either the declaration called also Declaration of Lima, as that had been previously announced.
On the official site of the ASPA, one can check that the document was published in the month of last March.
In both go international, the Peruvian authorities tried to set up sure systems of transmission for all the journalists, but they limited to the maximum obtaining of information.
The top was also concluded with the joint agreement from Chile and Peru to accept a judgement of the Court of The Hague which slices different frontier between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the time of the appointment regional and stated that they would respect the decision of the CIJ to hear the pleas of the two parts in the lawsuit that Lima brought against Santiago and who starts Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and carry out the verdict which will solve the disagreements that we carry today before this international court”, president Humala stated, at the side of his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile always was, and will continue to be a respectful country of the international law, peaceful resolution of the controversies, treaties and international courts”, president Piñera added by giving a handful of hand to president Humala, beside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents whom they would subject to the CIJ took place after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogota by which it had agreed to be subjected to the decisions of this international court, after a decision on the maritime limits with Nicaragua which it regarded as seriously erroneous.
The top was taken place without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, of Bolivia, Evo Morales, and of Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended of Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not take part in go.
The president host, Ollanta Humala, were charged to open the deliberations the morning and to close the top shortly after midday in Lima.
The agent read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been fixed between the South American countries for a total of 17 million dollars of investment.
Among the adopted agreements, it mentioned that the countries of Unasur would set up “important approachs to achieve the goal of the South American citizenship by the development of agreements on the residence permits”.
It informed that actions would be installation to improve the “co-operation in the fight against the urban insecurity and the international organized crime, of the actions for a better accessibility with the drugs, the access to the Internet at low prices in the totality of South America, and to evaluate in a joint and effective way the risks of natural disasters”.
With Europe in crisis, “the economic consolidation (of the Latin America) should not have a matrix triumphalist person but must help to increase our productive matrix and to foresee a better future for our populations”, president Humala concluded.
“We decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects which improve the connection of spaces of South America, in particular in the rural areas and frontier… by linking our countries and by generating new economic channels”, the president Peruvian at the time of a speech stated.
Among these projects, it mentioned that five related to Peru and were on the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador although it did not give fuller details.
In the same way, the final document mentions the political situation of Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its rehabilitation within the Union of the South American Nations”, from which it is currently excluded.
The need which the Latin America remains an area of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relationships with its neighbors, is another topic approached at the time of the top.
In this direction, the Colombian president, Juan Manuel Santos, stated, before beginning to it appointment regional, which he hoped to meet his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, saturdays following to Mexico City to discuss the maritime disagreement calmly through judgement of the CIJ requested by Bogota.
“It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I hold a meeting with president Daniel Ortega”, declared president Santos.
“We will revise all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will require to have a discussion with this country”, he underlined.
“I hope to be able to say to president Ortega whom we will regulate that in the possible most civilized and respectful way”, president Santos added.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City where they envisaged to attend the catch to be able of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Same manner, within the framework of the top, the Ministers for the Defense of the block will meet beforehand to approve the Action plan of the year 2013, which tries to reinforce the dialogue and the consensus in terms of defense in the area.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although this last country is suspended.
Peru takes the presidency pro tempore regional block.

